										<h2><a href="#">Proposing an Observation</a></h2>
										
										<p>
											e-MERLIN is open to observing proposals from the international astronomical community on the basis of scientific merit alone. There are several methods of submitting observing proposals.</p>
										<h1>Cycle Based Proposal Submission</h1>
											<p>
											Proposals can be submitted prior to each observing <i>Cycle</i> (there are currently two 6 month Cycles per year) in an invitation period during which time
											e-MERLIN invites the scientific community to submit experiments. Two main types of Cycle proposal options are available;
											 <li><b>Regular</b>; for experiments that can be observed at predictable times during the Cycle and ;
											<li><b>Targets of Opportunity (ToO)</b>
											; for experiments that require triggering by the Principal Investigator (PI). </li><br>
										Details regarding the size and structure of supporting proposal material uploaded to Cycle proposals are given in the explanatory notes on the e-MERLIN NorthStar proposal tool.
                                                                        <p>
                                                                           	Once a proposal is submitted it is competitively peer-reviewed by the e-MERLIN Time Allocation Group (TAG) under standard STFC rules.
                                                                                If the proposal successfully wins time with e-MERLIN it will be graded and forwarded to our team of schedulers who will use the graded priority to construct an appropriate schedule for queueing.
                                                                                You will not need to write a specific schedule yourself, although a member of the team may contact you to discuss any special requests. For example, amplitude and phase calibrators are determined by
                                                                                schedulers, unless you specify otherwise.
                                                                                e-MERLIN uses dynamic scheduling, meaning that the highest graded project does not necessarily mean it is the first observed, but rather it is optimised depending upon telescope availability.
                                                                                If you require e-MERLIN to be used within the European VLBI network, then your proposal should be submitted to the <a href="http://proposal.jive.nl" target="_blank">EVN</a> instead, with a specific request to include the e-MERLIN array.
                                                                                The data would be then correlated at the  <a href="http://www.jive.nl" target="_blank">Joint Institute for VLBI (JIVE)</a>.

                                                                        </p>

										<h1>Rapid Response Time Submission</h1>	
											In addition to Regular and ToO Cycle Time proposals, and specifically for urgent time-critical observations (i.e. unforeseen transient events not envisaged during proposal invitation periods),
											an additional route for proposing is now available via the <i> Rapid Response Time (RRT)</i>, designed to enhance e-MERLIN transient science.

											Such RRT requests are subject to the same assessment procedures by the e-MERLIN Time Allocation Group (TAG) as Cycle proposals. These will be performed soon after the RRT submission. Please note that existing approved Cycle ToOs programmes triggering on the same target will take precedence over RRT in any direct clash.  
RRT requests should be submitted by email to <a href="mailto:emerlin@jb.man.ac.uk?subject=RRT Request" span class="inline-flag"><b>emerlin@jb.man.ac.uk</b></span></a> with an attached scientific application with a length not exceeding two pages of text (including an abstract) outlining the science case together with the required urgency of the observations and cadence of the any follow-up runs. The text should have a minimum font size of 11. A third page may be included but only for any additional figures if required. 
									
									<br></p>
										<h1>Director's Discretionary Time (DDT)</h1>
										<p>	For other exceptional observations, the <i>Director's Discretionary Time</i> (DDT) is also an option, but these are reserved only for types of observation which do not fit within standard astronomical assessment criteria.
											
										</p>
									</header>
									
									<h2>Observing Frequencies</h2>

										<p>
											The three radio-frequency bands available in all modes for observing are:</p>
											<p></p>
											<ul>
											<li>L-Band (1.25 -1.75 GHz),</li>
											<li>C-Band (4.3 - 7.5 GHz) and </li>
											<li>K-Band (19 - 25 GHz).</li>
										</ul>
									<p>Proposals can include any of these bands and may also request inclusion of the 76 metre Lovell telescope (except at K-Band), 
									although this requires a demonstration of its necessity due to its more limited availability.
									<br></p>
